Sincerely yours, Zach Baer, subcommittee chair.

17
00:00:52,566 --> 00:00:53,626
Thank you for being here today.

18
00:00:54,227 --> 00:00:56,308
To my fellow councilors and to members of the city staff.

19
00:00:56,973 --> 00:01:15,138
We are meeting today on what I think is our third, maybe fourth meeting on the budget ordinance, definitely our second this fall, where we left the last meeting as we reviewed an ordinance draft prepared by this subcommittee, had what I would call a robust conversation on that draft for about an hour and a half.

20
00:01:16,338 --> 00:01:31,586
and we closed out with a motion to request that the chief of staff and the finance director provide a written response to the draft ordinance to be discussed at the next subcommittee meeting that includes a basic outline of what a reasonable timeline would look like for the budget process as discussed.

21
00:01:32,433 --> 00:01:34,915
And to add to that, I wanna say thank you.

22
00:01:35,195 --> 00:01:38,418
We got this document and I know you're gonna share it, but we have a document.

23
00:01:38,478 --> 00:01:40,219
I would say it goes beyond our request.

24
00:01:40,279 --> 00:01:42,221
I think it's a full updated draft.

25
00:01:42,241 --> 00:01:48,866
So I think that's really helpful for us to be able to consider tonight and going forward before the next budget season.

26
00:01:48,986 --> 00:01:55,891
So with that, if there are any counselors who would like to make any comments before I turn this over to the chief of staff and the finance director.

27
00:01:58,989 --> 00:02:02,490
Seeing that we just got this document, I'm still marking it up.

28
00:02:02,650 --> 00:02:06,672
And so if we could have the presentation, I'd be happy with that.

29
00:02:07,012 --> 00:02:07,252
Great.

30
00:02:07,792 --> 00:02:08,692
You good, Councilor Collins?

31
00:02:09,072 --> 00:02:09,332
Great.

32
00:02:09,952 --> 00:02:10,733
Madam Chief of Staff.

33
00:02:13,774 --> 00:02:23,396
Thank you very much to the members of the subcommittee on this subject and for the opportunity to discuss the presented ordinance that's before you.

34
00:02:23,976 --> 00:02:25,577
I do want to apologize for the

35
00:02:26,350 --> 00:02:28,911
time in which we're able to provide this draft.

36
00:02:28,971 --> 00:02:39,036
We had hoped to provide it earlier, but from a number of scheduling issues, you know, we were working on it this afternoon as well, to be candid, just putting some final aspects on it.

37
00:02:39,096 --> 00:02:43,859
So we were able to have a comprehensive and well thought out conversation with the subcommittee.

38
00:02:44,299 --> 00:02:45,840
So thank you for your patience.

39
00:02:46,020 --> 00:02:53,864
And obviously we're happy to continue the conversation beyond today and continue to work towards an ordinance that, you know, meets the

40
00:02:54,514 --> 00:03:09,445
objectives of the subcommittee and hopefully the city council as well as can fit within our current constraints and isn't something that is larger than we can manage today as we discussed at our last meeting.

41
00:03:10,426 --> 00:03:15,810
So from one of our take some of our takeaways from our last meeting included the

42
00:03:16,424 --> 00:03:29,149
after that lengthy discussion included the fact that the subcommittee stated that there were certain specific things that were most important to the city council as the subcommittee saw it.

43
00:03:29,809 --> 00:03:40,073
Specifically to have regular meetings and regular reporting, the earliest that the group could meet the possible, meaning the budget process and the city council.

44
00:03:40,827 --> 00:03:46,993
Um, the council to have an opportunity to provide input into the process before the final budget is formulated.

45
00:03:47,013 --> 00:03:53,178
Uh, and, you know, essentially a comprehensive proposal back to the city council.

46
00:03:53,238 --> 00:04:03,707
Those are the notes that I had jotted down at our last meeting as to the high level and most critical and important matters to this subcommittee and again, hopefully to the city council.

47
00:04:04,292 --> 00:04:22,165
So to that end, we've drafted, generally using the structure that was presented in the original draft, we've drafted what we believe to be aspects that are manageable and essentially feasible with today's staffing constraints and today's structures and today's systems.

48
00:04:23,365 --> 00:04:25,147
We all, I think, hope and I think

49
00:04:25,987 --> 00:04:43,836
The finance director and I, as well as the mayor, share the sentiment that we want to get even more sophisticated down the road, but we think that iterations down the road of this ordinance can be modified to accommodate that sophistication once we have the systems in place to be able to do so.

50
00:04:45,295 --> 00:04:46,656
So we're happy to walk through this.

51
00:04:47,176 --> 00:04:57,801
I mean, I'm happy to also either the finance director or I could give a high level overview of the sections that are here, if that would be helpful and kind of talk a little bit about the timelines.

52
00:04:58,662 --> 00:05:05,985
One thing that I will explicitly point out is that we have omitted aspects pertaining to the enterprise fund.

53
00:05:06,126 --> 00:05:10,968
And it was intentional because of the fact that our DPW commissioner and our water

54
00:05:11,418 --> 00:05:17,500
and sewer superintendent are, as you know, working on a strategic proposal plan and system.

55
00:05:17,940 --> 00:05:25,663
And there are a number of elements that need to come into play before I think we would recommend that anything be included here as far as the enterprise fund.

56
00:05:25,943 --> 00:05:32,446
But I think that that could be down the road and should be considered maybe a year from now as something that could be updated.

57
00:05:32,926 --> 00:05:37,248
But at this point in time, this would be just the main portions of the budget.

58
00:05:37,448 --> 00:05:40,309
We just don't want to put the cart before the horse and promise things that

59
00:05:41,228 --> 00:05:55,954
are being worked on parallel before the Water and Sewer Commission as well as the DPW Commissioner and his staff have had the opportunity to really give comprehensive thought and think through their process.

60
00:05:55,974 --> 00:05:57,215
So this is general fund only?

61
00:05:57,735 --> 00:05:57,935
Yeah.

62
00:05:58,335 --> 00:05:58,475
Yes.

63
00:05:58,715 --> 00:06:06,618
It's not to say that we wouldn't be attempting to follow similar timelines, but it's to say these things become law.

64
00:06:06,678 --> 00:06:09,720
These things become things we're required to follow.

65
00:06:10,845 --> 00:06:24,551
let's take our time setting the ones that we know we can accomplish and then move and augment this ordinance in the future when we know we have the systems in place to be able to do it again, because there's another body that comes into play with that as well.

66
00:06:25,912 --> 00:06:27,773
Just on that question, I mean, I think that makes sense.

67
00:06:27,793 --> 00:06:32,695
And we've heard from Commissioner McGivern and Superintendent Stone-King

68
00:06:33,386 --> 00:06:49,209
about the extensive, and to be frank, some of the water and sewer commissioners I've spoken to about the level of work that's going on there to get us into a place where we're, leave it at the fact that there are significant financial issues given the state of the system in the city.

69
00:06:51,430 --> 00:06:56,771
What about grant funding, revolving funds, special revenue funds?

70
00:06:58,591 --> 00:06:59,991
Just if we could speak to that as well.

71
00:07:00,011 --> 00:07:02,792
Has that also been excluded as a just general fund right here?

72
00:07:03,732 --> 00:07:04,112
right now?

73
00:07:04,333 --> 00:07:04,633
Yes.

74
00:07:04,953 --> 00:07:05,173
Yes.

75
00:07:05,354 --> 00:07:11,339
I mean, I can go on about why that is, but those in and of themselves are major undertakings.

76
00:07:11,880 --> 00:07:15,503
Um, so, I mean, I'm happy that we're happy to dive into any of those elements.

77
00:07:16,003 --> 00:07:20,327
Just want to be mindful as to the subcommittee's time considering your 7 p.m.

78
00:07:20,347 --> 00:07:20,608
meeting.

79
00:07:21,108 --> 00:07:21,488
Yeah, no.

80
00:07:21,528 --> 00:07:29,095
And I just think, um, and correct me if this is an oversimplification because I'm sure it's an oversimplification of your job.

81
00:07:30,504 --> 00:07:37,969
But there's the general fund, the enterprise fund, and then what I would term everything else, which I think is grants, revolving, special revenue, et cetera.

82
00:07:39,190 --> 00:07:48,016
You know, I think we feel comfortable, at least I personally feel comfortable with my understanding of where the enterprise fund is at and coming back in a year maybe and looking at how we could incorporate them in here.

83
00:07:48,556 --> 00:07:54,480
What do we think the timeline is on that other bucket of stuff, which I know is a little bit harder to pin down?

84
00:07:55,200 --> 00:07:59,023
I'm happy to start this conversation and then I defer to our finance director.

85
00:08:02,354 --> 00:08:04,715
One, just starting with revolving funds.

86
00:08:08,058 --> 00:08:14,122
Those are dynamic, that's a dynamic funding bucket, if you will.

87
00:08:14,642 --> 00:08:23,008
Unlike an operating fund where an appropriation is set out at the beginning of the year, and that appropriation is the maximum that can be spent essentially,

88
00:08:23,368 --> 00:08:25,049
and you have to manage to that number.

89
00:08:25,469 --> 00:08:31,494
The difference with a revolving fund is that it's dynamic and that revenue is coming in as revenues going out.

90
00:08:32,234 --> 00:08:45,883
So doing forecasting and being able to present budgets, having done that in another community on a smaller level, even, is, it's a bit of a brain shift.

91
00:08:46,003 --> 00:08:47,124
It requires more,

92
00:08:49,112 --> 00:08:50,753
more planning, more analysis.

93
00:08:51,354 --> 00:08:54,977
We haven't set up those kinds of systems here in Medford at this point.

94
00:08:55,157 --> 00:09:02,523
We obviously work with our departments to ensure that we're not exceeding the budgets that are spent and that the revolving fund is always in a healthy balance.

95
00:09:03,004 --> 00:09:13,312
However, because it's a different approach entirely, it will take a different, I mean, as an example, just to speak

96
00:09:13,725 --> 00:09:22,071
specific to what I had to implement in another community is they're completely different budget sheets that get generated to be able to develop budgets.

97
00:09:22,472 --> 00:09:36,902
And then navigating those budget sheets are not entirely straightforward because, well, the lookbacks on them are taking into consideration revenue that's come in in prior years, but the year that's being spent on, all the revenue hasn't come in as you're spending.

98
00:09:36,922 --> 00:09:37,543
So it's just

99
00:09:39,038 --> 00:09:44,171
It's going to require the city, a bit of time to be able to work on that one thing alone.

100
00:09:45,555 --> 00:09:50,417
The enterprise fund might be the thing that is discussed next year as a potential addition in my mind.

101
00:09:50,898 --> 00:10:15,070
And then later down the road, how could we add other elements such as revolving funds or other special revenue buckets would be my suggestion, because I just, at this point in time, being able to carry this is already going to be an added workload to a department that's trying to weed through

102
00:10:15,782 --> 00:10:19,783
some old historical challenges and clean up.

103
00:10:21,203 --> 00:10:33,626
And then adding on top of that other elements such as a revolving fund budget process, which has never existed in Medford, is just beyond our capability at this point in time.

104
00:10:33,726 --> 00:10:39,348
I just, as I said before, I think, or alluded to before, I think we need to crawl before we can walk in this case.

105
00:10:40,761 --> 00:10:48,803
And that's probably not the best metaphor, because I do believe that we've done a better job than in past decades in providing budget information to the council.

106
00:10:50,183 --> 00:10:55,685
But I recognize that the council's looking for more of a conversation on this matter, and I think we are able to accomplish that.

107
00:10:56,005 --> 00:10:59,946
And that's the metaphor that I'm using for crawling and walking, essentially, on this.

108
00:11:00,706 --> 00:11:01,066
Got it.

109
00:11:03,386 --> 00:11:09,608
And just to add to that, obviously, you're aware most of the special revenue funds

110
00:11:10,638 --> 00:11:24,228
are set up for specific grants that can be, the grant money can only be spent on that, whatever the grant is for, and they are unbudgeted.

111
00:11:24,308 --> 00:11:27,390
They can be spent without appropriation.

112
00:11:28,331 --> 00:11:30,012
So what

113
00:11:30,917 --> 00:11:40,260
my department's been doing is trying to go through each and every grant fund, special revenue fund to make sure that we're in compliance.

114
00:11:40,360 --> 00:11:42,181
That's what you're generally supposed to do.

115
00:11:42,341 --> 00:11:44,361
We're in compliance with what the grant is for.

116
00:11:44,421 --> 00:11:45,802
We work with the auditors on that.

117
00:11:46,402 --> 00:11:51,103
And then at the end of the day, the thing balances out.

118
00:11:51,144 --> 00:11:55,065
We've gotten revenue in to cover the expenses if it's a reimbursement fund.

119
00:11:55,185 --> 00:11:58,706
So when we're thinking about what exactly the council needs

120
00:11:59,918 --> 00:12:04,260
would need to see and would look at for special revenue funds.

121
00:12:04,620 --> 00:12:11,483
And remember in Medford, not even counting the school, there's probably a couple of hundred special revenue funds, grant funds.

122
00:12:11,523 --> 00:12:12,904
We get new ones every week.

123
00:12:14,344 --> 00:12:22,588
So that's more of an ongoing conversation about what type of information the council would need.

124
00:12:23,148 --> 00:12:23,448
Got it.

125
00:12:23,528 --> 00:12:23,768
Yeah.

126
00:12:23,968 --> 00:12:27,330
And I think just as one counselor, and sorry to belabor it,

127
00:12:28,643 --> 00:12:42,827
But both that and on that front, you know, we triage positions into revenue funds and we have grant funded positions that are essentially doing filling roles that we would like to see be operating positions.

128
00:12:43,447 --> 00:12:50,130
And I think my question is less aimed at how can we pigeonhole special revenue funds into this process?

129
00:12:50,210 --> 00:12:55,711
Because I understand that we're not gonna be able to budget in the same way and we can't rely on the funds in the same way.

130
00:12:56,211 --> 00:12:57,912
But to me, it's more to understand

131
00:13:00,296 --> 00:13:15,179
when we're triaging like that or when we have grant-funded positions that are filling operating budget roles in some sense, how are we, what's the impact of losing a grant on what the general fund need is, right?

132
00:13:15,339 --> 00:13:20,000
My biggest example I'm thinking about this year is ARPA and ARPA-funded positions.

133
00:13:20,220 --> 00:13:29,102
I'll leave ESSER and the schools to the school side, but we have a number of important positions funded through ARPA and understanding what the administration's plan is to

134
00:13:31,343 --> 00:13:33,504
essentially shift those onto the operating budget.

135
00:13:33,804 --> 00:13:49,890
So maybe not something as detailed as I understand exactly what you're saying is plugging it in and having the preliminary meetings, but at least understanding how we're gonna make sure that positions that we wanna keep in the longterm that are not funded in the general fund, what is the relationship there?

136
00:13:49,930 --> 00:13:56,833
How are we trying to shift those funds so that we can make sure that we can keep staff on in the longterm for roles that are longterm roles?

137
00:13:57,837 --> 00:14:07,479
And specifically to that, as you know, staffing with ARPA is only allowed through December 31st of next year.

138
00:14:07,979 --> 00:14:12,200
So as we're discussing the FY25 budget, all of that will become clear.

139
00:14:12,300 --> 00:14:16,621
We are actively working on this subject right now as it pertains to staff.

140
00:14:17,881 --> 00:14:26,883
We've been working with a number of different departments trying to pre-plan how we can ensure that those positions continue to support the city.

141
00:14:29,275 --> 00:14:42,322
and further information will shake out through the process, but it will all become evident as to how we're going to have to handle ARPA-funded positions in the fiscal 25 budget.

142
00:14:42,562 --> 00:14:47,885
And it is our goal to have those positions, to the best of our ability, continue to support city services.

143
00:14:48,225 --> 00:14:48,705
Understood.

144
00:14:48,725 --> 00:14:49,986
I'm going to pause there.

145
00:14:50,026 --> 00:14:51,167
I just wanted to get that framing in.

146
00:14:52,120 --> 00:15:03,214
Your draft here, we're talking general fund only, hopes in the future around enterprise, the other bucket, and I don't think we talked SIP here at all.

147
00:15:03,334 --> 00:15:06,659
So those would be future capital improvement plans.

148
00:15:06,699 --> 00:15:09,102
So those are future goals, but we're talking general fund right here.

149
00:15:09,931 --> 00:15:10,171
got it.

150
00:15:10,591 --> 00:15:17,734
Um, if you guys have questions, I can go to you now, but I also want to give you a chance to finish your presentation of the, of this before we go to questions.

151
00:15:18,054 --> 00:15:22,415
Well, I was just wishing for maybe I had two quick questions.

152
00:15:22,736 --> 00:15:34,880
Um, earlier on in the presentation, you mentioned that you like in different municipalities, there's some, um, some systems set in place with regards to like making it easier to look at these dynamic funds, these revolving funds.

153
00:15:35,800 --> 00:15:43,384
I was wondering, not that we have money for that, because we don't have money for those systems, to implement those systems, but I am curious what that would look like.

154
00:15:44,124 --> 00:15:54,250
And the second question would be, I guess, very similar to what Councilor Behrs was saying, was, is it possible to take

155
00:15:56,018 --> 00:16:05,044
you know, grant funded positions out of just like, instead of just talking about special funds, like, let's talk about special funds for staff personnel.

156
00:16:05,084 --> 00:16:10,028
Is that, is it possible to put that in here or is that too much of a lift?

157
00:16:13,160 --> 00:16:15,622
I'm happy to share my thoughts as usual.

158
00:16:15,982 --> 00:16:19,926
I'm not particularly shy, so forgive me for jumping in.

159
00:16:19,986 --> 00:16:25,230
But I mean, I can't speak, Councillor, saying to how it works in other communities.

160
00:16:25,290 --> 00:16:32,617
Frankly, the community that I was in had a revenue issue for certain revolving funds, so I had to implement the process to ensure that the

161
00:16:33,117 --> 00:16:40,944
revenue that the expenses weren't exceeding the revenues I can't speak to what other communities do because in the other communities that I worked in, there was no such process.

162
00:16:41,624 --> 00:16:46,528
So I've never seen one I actually built one in a much smaller community I defer to.

163
00:16:48,630 --> 00:16:51,231
our finance director on whether he's had that experience.

164
00:16:51,331 --> 00:17:01,594
As to the second question regarding staff positions, I mean, I think it largely becomes mute soon, but, you know, there are some minor areas where there is still support.

165
00:17:01,774 --> 00:17:07,155
You do see that information as it relates to transfers into the budget, for instance, casino mitigation funds.

166
00:17:07,835 --> 00:17:11,556
We've used it historically to pay for one engineering staff person.

167
00:17:12,176 --> 00:17:14,537
So that information is a part of the budget process.

168
00:17:15,062 --> 00:17:21,605
you know, the ARPA element, which is kind of the largest element, which is, you know, historically an unforeseen kind of funding source.

169
00:17:22,245 --> 00:17:28,488
And, you know, just kind of breaks the mold, if you will, of how we've historically operated.

170
00:17:28,548 --> 00:17:36,491
And for obvious reasons and good reasons, it won't be in the picture.

171
00:17:36,531 --> 00:17:42,634
So I don't know that it makes sense to, I wouldn't recommend it be incorporated into language, into an ordinance.

172
00:17:43,472 --> 00:17:50,165
Generally speaking, you know, guidance and advice from legal over the course of my career in developing.

173
00:17:51,144 --> 00:17:53,486
you know, what is essentially amounts to be a law.

174
00:17:53,706 --> 00:17:55,507
As we know, these ordinances become law.

175
00:17:56,087 --> 00:17:58,449
You want to be flexible with that.

176
00:17:58,549 --> 00:18:07,595
So you want to take into, it would be my recommendation that the council take into consideration there are things that are fluid that are going to change between today and in the future.

177
00:18:07,655 --> 00:18:20,463
And if ARPA is an element that's gonna change and it's the largest element that's on your mind, but otherwise the council is getting the sufficient information and it's no longer gonna be in the picture, I don't recommend it be incorporated into the ordinance.

178
00:18:21,668 --> 00:18:28,150
but I guess seeing as like, it's not gonna take up as big of a part of our, you know, staffing in the future.

179
00:18:28,950 --> 00:18:30,930
It just, I mean, this is my opinion.

180
00:18:30,950 --> 00:18:46,234
It just doesn't seem like huge lift to include some just information like that in the reports, especially if we're going down from like 50 positions from schools and for city side to like just a handful, it seems reasonable.

181
00:18:46,294 --> 00:18:49,875
And I guess like the flip side of what you were saying is in the future,

182
00:18:50,435 --> 00:19:14,357
You know, we, I mean, I know folks in Washington are talking about financial packages in the future that look like ARPA to municipalities, and it would seem to me to be good to have some system set in place before where we're already practicing on kind of lower stakes, lower, smaller amounts of work, you know, a lesser workload.

183
00:19:14,817 --> 00:19:17,339
in preparation to set those systems up for the future.

184
00:19:17,379 --> 00:19:19,341
But that's, I'll defer to the rest of the council.

185
00:19:20,002 --> 00:19:21,643
It's just my thoughts.

186
00:19:22,244 --> 00:19:23,044
Thank you, Councilor Sang.

187
00:19:23,805 --> 00:19:29,210
And if I'm incorrect, I'm not sure, and maybe we just need to double check on standard practice.

188
00:19:30,891 --> 00:19:36,937
When we get the staff charts in the budget proposal, do those charts include grant-funded positions?

189
00:19:38,078 --> 00:19:39,039
My recollection is yes.

190
00:19:39,139 --> 00:19:39,719
Yes, they do.

191
00:19:39,839 --> 00:19:40,800
Yeah, I thought they did.

192
00:19:42,952 --> 00:19:56,602
